vernacular images, both beautiful and appealing, strengthen our understanding of High Qing culture. They bring to light the Qing or Manchu emperors' fascination with erotic culture in the thriving cities of the Yangtze Delta and demonstrate the growth of figure painting in and around Beijing's imperial court. They also revise our understanding of gender roles and show how Chinese artists made use of European styles. By introducing a large, rich body of works, Pictures for Use and Pleasure opens new windows on later Chinese life and society.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aArt and societyzChinaxHistory. 0aGenre painting, ChinesexMing-Qing dynasties, 1368-1912. 0aGenre painting, Chinese. 4aArt. 4aAsian. 4aGeneral. 7aART / Asian / General.2bisacsh1 aCahill, James, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052025857040uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052094567840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520945678423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520945678/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles